Adjustment due to time. I find @Fueled_by_Gummybears ' comments about the posted schedule to be only mildly convincing in the given circumstances. This is because *if* (and it is a huge if) a significant change came about in the national election situation, the court would be highly likely to modify the schedule to that situation (as opposed to vice versa). Similarly, @erikbays ' comment about the base rate of how often "normal" Supreme Court cases go to oral argument is only somewhat informative because of the highly unusual nature of the current situation (to wit: the importance of the election system overall, ongoing legal efforts to discard large numbers of votes in the current election (https://www.texastribune.org/2020/12/08/texas-ken-paxton-election-georgia/), attempts and rhetoric about how the supreme court *in particular* is the desired venue that the President appears to be hoping to use to further their current purposes (See POTUS retweet amplification of this message, for example: https://twitter.com/Raiklin/status/1336319381547089922 etc). All that said, the weakness of the legal cases made thus far, the associated lack of evidence of voter fraud, the margin of the Biden electoral victory and Supreme Court institutional equities make the chance remain quite low.

The official government website states that SCOTUS hears about 70-80 cases per year, and those are most often on Mondays, Tuesdays, and Wednesdays, with two arguments per day. Therefore, there would be, under such a base rate, only 9 days / 18 cases as available opportunities remaining until 14 December. Another base rate assessment shows that of the available 70-80 cases heard per year (from October to April) ~12% of available opportunities are available, reinforcing the ~9-10 days / 18-20 case availability remaining. Importantly, while this is a very timely topic that could (and should) be prioritized if necessary, the collection of data required for making an oral argument is simply not going to be available in time (given the ongoing Senate race in Georgia as an example). Because that state would be necessary for a change in the election outcome, and the outcome of the state is still in progress, this becomes all the more unlikely. While President Trump has made repeated statements that the election outcome should be decided in the courts, often citing the 2000 election, there are significant differences between the 2000 election and the 2020 election. Primarily, the controversy in 2000 centered around a single state: Florida. For the 2020 outcome to be overturned (note: it is still not certified, though Biden is the likely winner), MULTIPLE states would need to have their projected outcome reversed. This seems out of step with the direction that Chief Justice Roberts has steered the high court [1]. Furthermore, the latest filing in PA by Trump's attorneys' will be heard by a judge appointed by Obama [2]. For this and a veriety of reasons, Trump's challenge may never reach the Supreme Court [3]. Beyond PA, Trump's legal challenges in other battleground states seem weak at best [4].

The Trump team would desperately love to get this in front of the Supreme court and there is enough time.
